commentBody:
@B

Three letter Giant--OTT
Four letters--ALOU

@SBK in TO

I walked though the tunnel from the PIE IX metro to the big O, and looked at the photos on the wall of the many different events that have taken place there over the years. For the Expos there's a photo of Youpi and a classic photo of Felipe, in his years as manager. It could be argued that a number of Expo players should be on the wall as well, but if I had to pick two, it would be Felipe Alou first and Youpi (tied with some others) in second. 

Felipe Alou had tremendous influence and popularity in Montreal in his day, mostly because of his character. He was a uniting force that we don't see very often.

@Weak

I'm also one of the 'dummies' who takes 25-35 but it took the normal amount for me.  

But I got stuck for a while in the top half because I had SET instead of LAP, COW instead of SOW and STAMP instead of TRAMP, and did not know who HASAN Piker was, which made it tough to get SURPRISE PARTIES.

@Moira

Yeah, of all of Rebecca's many clues, they couldn't find one a little less jarring?? 

I really liked [Functions without awareness?] for its Friday crunchiness. What an aha moment that would've made! I still enjoyed the answer, but with a heavy dose of relief-!

@Mos

Oh wow, was that in the column?  Much much better clue.

Really need Constructors' Editions these days.

@Ed

It bears noting that Giant Jesus, alongside his brothers Matty and Felipe, composed the only ever all-brother outfield in the history of the great American pastime for eight games in 1963.

This was a great clue in an otherwise one-cerebral-heisphere-tied-behind-your-back Friday.

@Matt
If it makes it through the emu gauntlet, I also posted about Felipe Alou with Les Expos, including the rare privilege of managing his own son Moise Alou as player.
I'd also recommend the recent documentary, "Who Killed the Expos?" which features a lot of Alou footage. SPOILER ALERT: MLB did it through its stooge Jeffrey Luria.

@Becky,

As your friend Matt said after me, this was a great clue. My only thought was “Christ of the Andes”. I mean, what else could it be? 

Then I thought of ALOU, and the rest is history.

@Matt

Nah, you like it, Mattster. It reminds you of what it was like to be young and carefree, once, long ago. 

Cool last century story about Pele.

@Matt

Good to remember them now, while you still can. 

💀

@Harrison

It's a boring clue already, IMHO. Getting the answer, down there at the bottom of the grid, was a final letdown when it could've been so much sharper! 

Complete opposite of [Giant Jesus], which is so concise *and* clever.

@dutchiris

Agreed. Nice puzzle but I went through it in no time. (Hardest challenge: I didn't know the Hillary Clinton dance and had TRoMP instead of TRAMP. Fixed that in no time too.)

My personal marker is when I've filled in complete crossing entries without even having looked at them, it's too easy. For me. For the day in question.

@Andrzej my solve time was 30% of average and ~50% of recent ‘normal’ Fridays. So it felt speedy. 

Wednesday took longer than today. 

Haven’t had cash on me for quite a while now. I just checked and there’s an emergency 20€ in my hat 😀

@Times Rita

Someone's cruisin' for an "OK, Boomer!"

Not gonna be from me.

@Times Rita

To be honest, had my parent's not had successful carreers after the transformation of 1989 that funded the family's quite indulgent lifestyle, I probably would not have heard of a scallop, either.

I try not to judge people but what they do and do not know. We all have such different life experiences that lead us down so many different paths - as a privileged white guy with a doctorate and no debts, I have the background and I can afford the time and experiences to learn all kinds of stuff, but not everybody enjoys such circumstances.

@Esmerelda

The clue did not make it clear that it was about baseball.  But it was a giant of a clue.

(The clue would have been at the same time more accurate and more obvious if Jesus had an accent mark on the u.)

@Rod

The ALOU brothers have been kept alive by crossword constructors for many years.  If you're a regular solver, it's a name worth remembering.

@Esmerelda
The other 4-letter baseball name, that appears with almost equal regularity, is A-ROD.  Perhaps @Rod knows that one!

Of course, there's also Mays and Rose and Orel

@Don H

Game refuges (or game reserves) allow hunting of animals, so they don't sound like places the animals might consider to be a sanctuary.  

The term "game" seems to imply that they are a product rather than a customer.

@Jane Wheelaghan

Your unknown names were also American-centered.  It's not surprising that the puzzle is more difficult for international solvers.  But a four-lettered baseball player (assuming you got that it was about baseball, which is not a given) is almost always ALOU in Crossworld.

You were at an advantage with SCOT and WATT, although the latter is quite well-known here, and the former should be known by anyone who has a good background in history.

@The X-Phile
@Mu

Commented earlier that i had 

__URP RIcE PAtTIES - with not only cOW but stAMP as stumbling points. 😂

Even with HA_AN at the top, I struggled to fill that missing letter because I’d never heard of Mr Piker.

@D

A very hyperbolic take on the complaint that the late-week puzzles of today are consistently much easier than those of 3-5 years back and downright laughers compared to 10 years back.  One only has to go to the archives and solve to see the truth of this statement.

How complaining about this translates for you into making people feel they are not wanted is a mystery to me.

@Heidi

Speaking of not belonging here, a lengthy-ish response I wrote to your comment has been deleted.

As far as this comments section goes, *nobody* really belongs here 🤣

@Anonymous

Yeah, but @Heidi in Dallas is an experienced solver — more than her post implies — and a regular commenter. So while your comment is very good advice, there may be something else to her post.  :)

Speaking for myself, while I felt let down by this puzzle given who the constructors are, it's equally disheartening to come to the Wordplay comments only to find them overwhelmed by the complaints about difficulty. It wasn't *that* bad, nor *that* easy. Yet in lieu of personal anecdotes or praise of clever gems, there's just a large amount of repetitive commentary. I wish the Games staff would get the message already so we all can move on!

@Heidi 

For what it's worth, I always enjoy your comments! You definitely belong! 

But I also absolutely get it, because there are days I feel like that too.

