I hope you're having a lovely Ostara. For those who didn't know, that's the (German) pagan celebration of the Vernal Equinox, and the reason why we have dyed eggs and bunnies for Easter. Also, Spring cleaning.

I hope your husband doesn't call you a SATANISt.

@Grant

I think we have spring cleaning because of Passover, the celebration of which precedes Easter by just a few years.  Observant Jews have to do a thorough cleaning of their houses in order to get rid of chametz, which is anything containing foods forbidden on the holiday.

(Because most desserts on Passover are made without wheat flour, almost everything in that category is GLUTEN FREE.)

@Barry Ancona

I'm in the same boat.

I noted the clue said "the grain," which tipped me off that it might be referring to a specific grain instead of to "low carb" or "Paleo," which didn't fit anyway. "Going against three grains" would have been more accurate but not as fun.

@Scott

It's not all that hard.  They apparently have rounds of private beta test solvers, in addition to a staff of editors.  They know how hard something is going to be before they publish it, they edit for difficulty and clarity all the time, and they know that they are making them easier.

Do you enjoy solving kid menu placemat puzzles AS MUCH as NYT crosswords?

@retired, with cat

I'm with you.  With the Washington Post being an ex-newspaper, the NYT is about all we have other than the Wαll Street Journαl, which is a sworn enemy of those not ultra-wealthy (remember the WSJ's editorial about "lucky duckies" who were so poor they didn't have to have to pay income taxes? Just sales tax and property tax and tariff taxes, and FICA taxes...)

If the NYT is actually staying afloat based on new Games subscriptions because the puzzles are easier (which I'm not sure I believe), then maybe it's just a price we have to pay for this dark moment.

